{{Infobox person | image = <!-- [[Freely licenced]] images only. NO SCREEN CAPTURES. Please do not put a fair-use image here, it will be deleted - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> | name = Mindy Cohn | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1966|05|20}} | birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S. | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Actress, voice actress, comedian, singer | yearsactive = 1979–present | alma_mater = [[Loyola Marymount University]] | residence = [[Beverly Hills, California]] | spouse = | website = }} '''Mindy Cohn''' (born May 20, 1966) is an American [[actress]], [[voice actress]], [[comedian]] and [[singer]]. She is known for her role as [[List of The Facts of Life characters#Natalie Green|Natalie Green]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[The Facts of Life (TV series)|The Facts of Life]]'',<ref> {{cite news |title= This Weeks Picks |publisher= The Washington Post |page= Y03 |date= 2004-03-07}}</ref> and for being the voice of [[Velma Dinkley]] in the ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'' franchise from 2002 to 2015. She resides in [[Beverly Hills]].<ref> {{cite episode | title = [[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]] | airdate = 2006-05-09 | transcripturl= http://web.lexis-nexis.com/universe/document?_m=8b7e68709164dfca48918b4151f55928&_docnum=1&wchp=dGLbVlz-zSkVA&_md5=242abeb042c84b4e97bb63620a09eaf5 }} </ref>
==Early life and career== Cohn was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], in 1966, and was raised Jewish.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mindy-cohn/why-me-why-now-why-not_b_3223346.html?ir=Yahoo | work=Huffington Post | first=Mindy | last=Cohn | title=How I Completely Accidentally Serendipitously Became A Teenage Sitcom Star | date=2013-05-07}}</ref> She was discovered by actress [[Charlotte Rae]] when Rae and the producers of ''The Facts of Life'' visited [[Harvard-Westlake School|Westlake School]] in [[Bel Air, Los Angeles|Bel Air, California]], while doing research for the show.<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www.onmilwaukee.com/family/articles/charlotterae.html?page=2 | title = Milwaukee Talks Charlotte Rae
| accessdate = 2007-06-23 | author = Molly Snyder Edler | publisher = www.onmilwaukee.com }} </ref> Cohn was cast as Natalie Green and portrayed the character for the series' entire run (1979–88), as well as in the reunion movie (2001).<ref> {{cite news |title= Facts of Life remain the Same |publisher= Toronto Star |page= D02 |date= 2001-11-18}}</ref> Her work on ''The Facts of Life'' was honored when she was ranked 43rd on VH1's List of 100 Greatest Kid Stars.<ref> {{cite news |title= VH1 Names Gary Coleman the Greatest Kid Star |publisher= prnewswire.com |date= 2005-06-05}}</ref>
In 2013, she commented on Charlotte Rae's lobbying on her behalf: "Mr. Reynolds calls me into his office. It seemed that Charlotte Rae had fallen madly in love with me, in part because I reminded her of her best childhood friend Natalie — and I was irrepressible, charming, and hilarious. So she asked the producers to create a part for me in the show. Honestly, the whole thing seemed so fantastic I didn’t know what to think."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mindy-cohn/why-me-why-now-why-not_b_3223346.html|title=Why Me? Why Now? Why Not|publisher=Huffington Post.com|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2016}}</ref>
After the show, she still remained friends with Rae. Just 2 months before her acting mentor's 90th Birthday in 2016, when Cohn was unavailable to attend ''The Facts of Life'' reunion interview, she even bestowed Rae a video message praising her decades-long friend for teaching Cohn the craft of acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hallmarkchannel.com/home-and-family/monday-february-15th-2016|title=Home & Family's "Facts of Life" Reunion|publisher=Hallmark Channel.com|date=February 15, 2016|accessdate=November 20, 2016}}</ref>
==Education== {{expand section|date=September 2015}} Cohn has a degree in [[cultural anthropology]] from [[Loyola Marymount University]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.televisionhits.com/factsoflifereunion/presskit.html | title = ABC Presskit for "The Facts of Life Reunion" movie | accessdate = 2007-06-23}} </ref> and is a founding member of the weSpark [[cancer]] support center.<ref> {{cite web |url = http://www.wespark.org/about/our_founders.html |title = Our Founders |accessdate = 2007-06-23 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070523053701/http://www.wespark.org/about/our_founders.html |archivedate = May 23, 2007 |df = mdy-all }} </ref>
==Later career== Cohn has continued her acting career outside of ''The Facts of Life''. In 1984 she had a leading role as the daughter alongside Stockard Channing in RKO's video production of "Table Settings". In 1986, she appeared in ''[[The Boy Who Could Fly]]'' playing the part of Geneva. She also had guest appearances in other popular TV shows, including ''[[Charles in Charge]]'' (playing Buddy's sister Bunny, a young [[alcoholic]], in the 1988 episode "Bottle Baby"), and two guest appearances in the second season of the cop drama ''[[21 Jump Street]]'' (playing Rosa in the 1987 episode "Christmas In Saigon" and the 1988 episode "Chapel of Love"). In 2004 Cohn appeared in the WB comedy ''[[The Help (TV series)|The Help]]''. In 2010, Cohn played the role of Violet, the leading character in [[Casper Andreas]]'s movie ''[[Violet Tendencies]],'' and appeared on the Season 8 premiere of [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]]'s ''[[What Not to Wear (US TV series)|What Not to Wear]]'' on October 29, 2010. She appeared in an episode of ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'' on July 13, 2011, on ''[[The Secret Life of the American Teenager]]'' on March 26, 2012, and in ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]'' on May 21, 2014.
Cohn said that one of the reasons she did ''[[The Facts of Life Reunion#The Facts of Life Reunion|The Facts of Life Reunion]]'' in 2001 was that the actors in the long-running series have been wrongly denied a cut of the [[Syndication (television)|syndication]] and [[DVD]] profits from the series. "We all never got paid and still don't get paid for DVDs and reruns ... we felt we were owed."<ref> {{cite news | url = http://blogs.dailynews.com/outinhollywood/2008/03/11/mindy-cohn-greg-catches-up-wna/ | title= Mindy Cohn: Greg catches up w/Natalie from "The Facts of Life" | work= dailynews.com | date= 2008-03-11 | accessdate = 2015-09-21 | author = Greg Hernandez }}</ref>
Cohn reprised her Velma Dinkley role in ''[[Lego Dimensions]]''.<ref>{{cite video game | developer=[[Traveller's Tales]] | publisher=[[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]] | scene=Closing credits, 4:45 in, Voiceover Talent | title=[[Lego Dimensions]] | year=2015}}</ref>
==Personal life== Cohn has never married and has no children.<ref name="huffpost">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mindy-cohn/why-me-why-now-why-not_b_3223346.html|title=Why Me? Why Now? Why Not?&nbsp;{{!}}&nbsp;Mindy Cohn|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|last=Cohn|first=Mindy|authorlink=Mindy Cohn|date=July 7, 2013|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name="advocate">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/film/2010/07/08/no-shrinking-violet|title=No Shrinking Violet {{!}} Advocate.com|work=[[The Advocate]]|publisher=[[Here Media]]|last=Voss|first=Brandon|authorlink=Brandon Voss|date=July 8, 2010|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name="pridesource">{{cite web|url=http://www.pridesource.com/article.html?article=45702|title=PrideSource -|work=[[Between the Lines (newspaper)|PrideSource]]|publisher=Pride Source Media Group|last=Paull|first=Anthony|date=March 3, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref> She is also a strong supporter of the [[LGBT community]] and has stated that she is proud to be a "[[fag hag]]."<ref name="advocate">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/film/2010/07/08/no-shrinking-violet|title=No Shrinking Violet {{!}} Advocate.com|work=[[The Advocate]]|publisher=[[Here Media]]|last=Voss|first=Brandon|authorlink=Brandon Voss|date=July 8, 2010|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name="pridesource"/>
==Accolades== In 2003 Cohn was nominated for a [[30th Daytime Emmy Awards|Daytime Emmy Award]] for her work on the TV show ''[[What's New, Scooby-Doo?]]'', for which she provided the voice of [[Velma Dinkley]].<ref> {{cite news |title= 30th Daytime Emmy Awards |work= Washington Post |page= Y06 |date= 2003-05-01}}</ref> She reprised her role of Velma on ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]]'' and in several ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'' movies.
She received a positive notice from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' for her role in the 2007 [[Daniel Waters (screenwriter)|Daniel Waters]]' comedy film ''[[Sex and Death 101]]''.<ref> {{cite news | url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117933963.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 | title =Sex and Death 101 | accessdate = 2007-06-23 | first = Ken| last = Eisner | publisher = www.variety.com | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305134451/http://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/sex-and-death-101-1200558422/ | archivedate = March 5, 2016 | date=2007-06-20}} </ref>
